We consider three modes of detachment:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Simultaneous detachment:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All hairs detach simultaneously when ùúÉ = 0¬∞.
 Here the hairy pad shows the maximum possible adhesion, given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{adh}=N_{t}f_{p}\label{eq:simul_detach}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Sequential detachment:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When ùúÉ > 0¬∞, the hairs will detach sequentially from left to right (Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Schematic"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Let us consider the situation when the left most spring is stretched to
 its maximum length, l
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
h,p
\end_layout

\end_inset

, just before pull-off.
 The net force on the pad when n hairs are in contact with the surface is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{net}=\stackrel[i=1]{n}{\sum}k_{h}\left(l_{h,i}-l_{h,0}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be simplified into:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{net}=nf_{p}-\frac{n\left(n-1\right)}{2}k_{h}w\sin\theta & \qquad & n\geq N_{t}\label{eq:seq_detach}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seq_detach"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 describes the net force required to detach the left most hair.
 The maximum adhesion force for given N
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
t
\end_layout

\end_inset

 hairs can then be calculated as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{adh} & = & \left\{ \begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{f_{p}}{2}\left[\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}w\sin\theta}+1\right]+\frac{k_{h}w\sin\theta}{8} & \qquad & N_{t}\geq N_{max}\\
N_{t}f_{p}-\frac{N_{t}\left(N_{t}-1\right)}{2}k_{h}w\sin\theta & \qquad & N_{t}<N_{max}
\end{array}\right.\label{eq:seq_adh}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{max}=\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}w\sin\theta}+\frac{1}{2}\label{eq:n_max}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, N
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
max
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the number of hairs required to get maximum adhesion at a fixed tilt
 angle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Detachment propagation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a hair detaches from the surface, the backing layer undergoes an elastic
 recoil due to an unbalanced force.
 Suppose the backing layer spring relaxes upward by a length Œîl (Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Schematic"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 For n hairs in contact, the force balance before and after a hair detaches
 is given respectively by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\stackrel[i=1]{n}{\sum}k_{h}\left(l_{h,i}-l_{h,0}\right)=k_{b}\left(l_{b}-l_{b,0}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\stackrel[i=1]{n-1}{\sum}k_{h}\left(l_{h,i}+\Delta l-l_{h,0}\right)=k_{b}\left(l_{b}-\Delta l-l_{b,0}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving the above two equations for Œîl, we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta l=\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}\left(n-1\right)+k_{b}}\label{eq:backing_deform}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The length difference between the detached hair and its adjacent hair just
 before it breaks contact is 
\begin_inset Formula $w\sin\theta$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l>w\sin\theta$
\end_inset

, the adjacent hair will be stretched more than l
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
h,p
\end_layout

\end_inset

and thus also detach.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:backing_deform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows that Œîl increases for lesser number of hairs in contact.
 This implies that hair detachment will propagate and the pad completely
 breaks contact with the surface.
 The critical number of hairs, N
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
c
\end_layout

\end_inset

, necessary for detachment propagation at a given tilt angle is thus given
 by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{c}=\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}w\sin\theta}-\frac{k_{b}}{k_{h}}+1\label{eq:prop_nc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, for a given pad with N
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
t
\end_layout

\end_inset

 hairs, the critical tilt angle below which detachment propagates is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{c}=\arcsin\left[\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}w}\left(\frac{1}{\frac{k_{b}}{k_{h}}+N-1}\right)\right]\label{eq:prop_thetac}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hairs will propagate when n < N
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
c
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or ùúÉ < ùúÉ
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
c
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 If we assume the hairs to be softer than the backing layer (i.e.
 k
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
b
\end_layout

\end_inset

/k
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
h
\end_layout

\end_inset

 > 1), then from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:n_max"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:prop_nc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we get N
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
c
\end_layout

\end_inset

 < N
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
max
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This implies that, for a given pad with N
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
t
\end_layout

\end_inset

 hairs, the adhesion force will be given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seq_adh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, as before.
 The backing layer deformation has no effect on the adhesion.
 It only affects the dynamics by spontaneous detachment of hairs when n
 < N
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
c
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or ùúÉ < ùúÉ
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
c
\end_layout

\end_inset

, independent of the retraction speed.
\end_layout

